Susan Pope and Kathryn Kendrick represented Merck & Company, Inc. n/k/a Merck Sharp & Dohme Corp. (“Merck”) in a proposed class action brought by Kentucky residents who purchased and used the drug Vioxx.  The trial court had certified the class finding “a common nucleus of facts from which the potential plaintiffs’ claims arise” because all of the potential plaintiffs were prescribed Vioxx by doctors who relied on Merck’s assertion that it was safe and effective.  By unanimous panel Opinion issued Feb. 2, 2012, the Court of Appeals overruled the trial court’s certification of the class.  The Court of Appeals held that individual proof would be necessary to show that Merck had made fraudulent or negligent misrepresentations toward each class member through the marketing and sale of Vioxx and that each putative class member’s physician relied on the representations in prescribing Vioxx to each individual plaintiff.  This was the first appeal of a class certification order filed with the Kentucky Court of Appeals under Kentucky’s new Civil Rule 23 creating an interlocutory appeal process for class certification rulings that became effective Jan. 1, 2011.  Finding that common questions of fact would not predominate over these individualized issues, the Court found that a class action was not a superior mechanism in which to try the class members’ claims under CR 23.02(c).  



